00:17:03.490 --> 00:17:06.220
AMJAD ALI KHAN: While
playing the sarod,

00:17:06.220 --> 00:17:10.404
I'm not pressing the
string with my fingertips.

00:17:10.404 --> 00:17:15.530
While it's played with
fingertips-- cello, sitar--

00:17:15.530 --> 00:17:18.410
but if I play sarod
with fingertips,

00:17:18.410 --> 00:17:21.608
it will sound like this.

00:17:21.608 --> 00:17:23.576
[PLUCKING SAROD]

00:17:29.490 --> 00:17:31.830
So this is the
sound of fingertips.

00:17:31.830 --> 00:17:34.880
But to bring out the
human expressions,

00:17:34.880 --> 00:17:38.930
the vocal expressions, I have to
press the string with the edge

00:17:38.930 --> 00:17:40.640
of my fingernails.

00:17:40.640 --> 00:17:44.924
You can see the difference.

00:17:44.924 --> 00:17:46.920
[PLUCKING SAROD]

00:17:46.920 --> 00:17:48.916
[STRUMMING SAROD]

00:18:14.410 --> 00:18:16.810
Most of the songs--

00:18:16.810 --> 00:18:21.990
they are based on
language, text, lyrics.

00:18:21.990 --> 00:18:25.050
But in 13th century,
Hazrat Amir Khusro,

00:18:25.050 --> 00:18:30.390
a Sufi saint who created
[INAUDIBLE] called Qalbana.

00:18:30.390 --> 00:18:34.480
He created a style of
singing called Tarana.

00:18:34.480 --> 00:18:39.550
So Tarana doesn't deal with
language or lyrics or text.

00:18:39.550 --> 00:18:42.310
So he created a language
of music, language

00:18:42.310 --> 00:18:44.920
of syllables and sound.

00:18:44.920 --> 00:18:45.970
[TARANA SOUNDS]

00:18:48.190 --> 00:18:52.420
Just two compositions
I would like to sing--

00:18:52.420 --> 00:18:54.466
9 and 1/2 beat.

00:18:54.466 --> 00:18:56.890
