But the great
maestros, they became

00:44:08.410 --> 00:44:11.229
famous because of 3-minutes
record-- that 78 RPM.

00:44:11.229 --> 00:44:12.270
SRIDHAR RAMASWAMY: Right.

00:44:12.270 --> 00:44:13.769
AMJAD ALI KHAN:
That three minutes--

00:44:13.769 --> 00:44:15.760
the music is the
name of quantity.

00:44:15.760 --> 00:44:18.430
It doesn't matter how
many ragas you know.

00:44:18.430 --> 00:44:23.450
But even if you know four
ragas which are appealing,

00:44:23.450 --> 00:44:26.740
which are soothing and
give you pleasure--

00:44:26.740 --> 00:44:29.680
so music should be appealing.

00:44:29.680 --> 00:44:33.341
And that is most important.

00:44:33.341 --> 00:44:35.590
SRIDHAR RAMASWAMY: Do you
have any audience questions?

00:44:35.590 --> 00:44:38.352
I have an endless list to ask.

00:44:38.352 --> 00:44:40.560
AMJAD ALI KHAN: Feel free
to us whatever you want to.

00:44:43.314 --> 00:44:46.390
AUDIENCE: [SANSKRIT]--

00:44:46.390 --> 00:44:48.520
AMJAD ALI KHAN: Just take
the mic down a little.

00:44:48.520 --> 00:44:51.250
AUDIENCE: Welcome
again to Google.

00:44:51.250 --> 00:44:56.575
So my question was, obviously,
music was in the family.

00:44:56.575 --> 00:45:00.150
You were introduced
very early on.

00:45:00.150 --> 00:45:02.680
And sarod was obvious
choice, probably.

00:45:02.680 --> 00:45:05.900
But do you play other
instruments for fun?

00:45:05.900 --> 00:45:08.157
Or just pick things up?

00:45:08.157 --> 00:45:09.490
AMAAN ALI BANGASH: It's for him?

00:45:09.490 --> 00:45:09.956
AUDIENCE: What do you play?

00:45:09.956 --> 00:45:10.422
AMJAD ALI KHAN: You should--

00:45:10.422 --> 00:45:11.338
AUDIENCE: For you two.

00:45:11.338 --> 00:45:12.950
And of course, [INAUDIBLE]

00:45:12.950 --> 00:45:14.650
AMJAD ALI KHAN: You
start from Ayaan.

00:45:14.650 --> 00:45:17.140
AYAAN ALI BANGASH: Well,
I can strum the guitar.

00:45:17.140 --> 00:45:18.850
I can just,
literally, play around

00:45:18.850 --> 00:45:21.490
with the guitar, because
I play the sarod.

00:45:21.490 --> 00:45:23.280
And when you have the
frets it's easier.

00:45:23.280 --> 00:45:25.180
I can play around
with the sitar.

00:45:25.180 --> 00:45:27.280
It's those fun moments.

00:45:27.280 --> 00:45:29.680
It's not something I'm proud of.

00:45:29.680 --> 00:45:32.650
But obviously, we've had--

00:45:32.650 --> 00:45:34.600
I can play some compositions.

00:45:34.600 --> 00:45:37.930
We've heard so much music of
all my father's contemporaries.

00:45:37.930 --> 00:45:40.600
So we know how they would
hold the instrument, how--

00:45:40.600 --> 00:45:43.017
these were our heroes, along
with my father, all his--

00:45:43.017 --> 00:45:44.350
AMJAD ALI KHAN: May I interrupt?

00:45:44.350 --> 00:45:45.135
AYAAN ALI BANGASH: --all
his contemporaries.

00:45:45.135 --> 00:45:45.635
Yes.

00:45:45.635 --> 00:45:47.360
AMJAD ALI KHAN:
From his childhood,

00:45:47.360 --> 00:45:49.024
he was interested in painting.

00:45:49.024 --> 00:45:50.440
AYAAN ALI BANGASH:
Well, that too.

00:45:50.440 --> 00:45:54.670
AMJAD ALI KHAN: So always
the images of Lord Ganesha.

00:45:54.670 --> 00:45:58.840
And even his [INAUDIBLE]--

00:45:58.840 --> 00:46:01.990
that is his passion also.

00:46:01.990 --> 00:46:04.080
And he's involved
in painting also.

00:46:04.080 --> 00:46:05.137
Yes, what about you?

00:46:05.137 --> 00:46:06.970
AMAAN ALI BANGASH: No--
so you were saying--

00:46:06.970 --> 00:46:07.320
AYAAN ALI BANGASH: No, no.

00:46:07.320 --> 00:46:08.920
So that's pretty much it-- yes.

00:46:08.920 --> 00:46:13.270
AMAAN ALI BANGASH: So I think
sarod was an obvious choice--

00:46:13.270 --> 00:46:15.100
sorry-- [INAUDIBLE]
was an obvious choice,

00:46:15.100 --> 00:46:16.657
because there was
so much around it.

00:46:16.657 --> 00:46:18.740
It's like, when you're in
the middle of the ocean,

00:46:18.740 --> 00:46:19.780
you have to swim.

00:46:19.780 --> 00:46:21.460
There's no other option.

00:46:21.460 --> 00:46:24.690
But I enjoy playing
the tabla a little bit.

00:46:24.690 --> 00:46:26.690
AYAAN ALI BANGASH: He
plays very well, actually.

00:46:26.690 --> 00:46:28.000
AMAAN ALI BANGASH: But just,
like, [INAUDIBLE] tabla,

00:46:28.000 --> 00:46:28.480
we call it.

00:46:28.480 --> 00:46:30.080
AYAAN ALI BANGASH: Yeah,
a sample sound check--

00:46:30.080 --> 00:46:30.410
AMAAN ALI BANGASH: I'm OK--

00:46:30.410 --> 00:46:31.240
AYAAN ALI BANGASH:
--we'll have in a moment.

00:46:31.240 --> 00:46:33.489
AMAAN ALI BANGASH: --with a
bit of piano and composing

00:46:33.489 --> 00:46:36.220
some sort of songs and
all, and a bit of santoor.

00:46:36.220 --> 00:46:38.170
So it's there, but
it's not something

00:46:38.170 --> 00:46:40.000
that I can do it in
front of all of you.

00:46:40.000 --> 00:46:41.422
But it's like, a
bathroom singer.

00:46:41.422 --> 00:46:43.130
AYAAN ALI BANGASH:
Private moments-- yes.

00:46:43.130 --> 00:46:45.460
AMAAN ALI BANGASH: But
sarod was an obvious choice.

00:46:45.460 --> 00:46:48.810
AMJAD ALI KHAN: And I was
so much involved with tabla.

00:46:48.810 --> 00:46:53.150
I used to play tabla as
a child, and so tabla

00:46:53.150 --> 00:46:54.280
that my father got worried.

00:46:54.280 --> 00:46:58.180
He thought I might become only
tabla player, not sarod player.

00:46:58.180 --> 00:47:01.450
So he hid the tabla
for a long time.

00:47:01.450 --> 00:47:03.560
AMAAN ALI BANGASH:
He was tabla sick.

00:47:03.560 --> 00:47:05.830
AMJAD ALI KHAN: But
I'm so much involved.

00:47:05.830 --> 00:47:08.010
I enjoy playing tabla
in my free time.

00:47:08.010 --> 00:47:10.210
And I compose also--

00:47:10.210 --> 00:47:13.900
songs, [INAUDIBLE],, and
music for the ballet,

00:47:13.900 --> 00:47:15.820
music for the orchestra.

00:47:15.820 --> 00:47:19.570
And it's very interesting
how the industry works--

00:47:19.570 --> 00:47:22.605
even in Bombay,
film or Bollywood--

00:47:22.605 --> 00:47:25.240
that first, there is a tune.

00:47:25.240 --> 00:47:27.340
That tune is sent
to the lyricist.

00:47:27.340 --> 00:47:29.530
And then he wires the words.

00:47:29.530 --> 00:47:32.156
Like, I composed one song--

00:47:32.156 --> 00:47:55.130
[VOCALIZATION] So this is the
[INAUDIBLE] the first piece.

00:47:55.130 --> 00:47:57.767
And the lyricist wrote--

00:47:57.767 --> 00:47:59.100
AMAAN ALI BANGASH: [INAUDIBLE]--

00:47:59.100 --> 00:48:02.050
AYAAN ALI BANGASH: I don't
remember the words-- yeah.

00:48:02.050 --> 00:48:03.570
AMJAD ALI KHAN: "Dun"--

00:48:03.570 --> 00:48:05.550
anyway, so this is the--

00:48:08.690 --> 00:48:12.090
we always forget the language,
the words, the lyrics.

00:48:12.090 --> 00:48:17.610
Because our life is
full of sound and music.

00:48:17.610 --> 00:48:20.970
And in our traditional
families, we

00:48:20.970 --> 00:48:24.690
were not allowed
to plan our future.

00:48:24.690 --> 00:48:26.670
It's an unwise thing to do.

00:48:26.670 --> 00:48:30.700
But that is the commitment
the guru demands, that one

00:48:30.700 --> 00:48:32.170
has to surrender to gurus.

00:48:32.170 --> 00:48:34.420
One has to surrender to God.

00:48:34.420 --> 00:48:36.700
And rest-- leave it to God.

00:48:36.700 --> 00:48:38.840
We don't know what is
going to happen tomorrow.

00:48:38.840 --> 00:48:42.540
So there was our way of life
of Indian classical musicians.

00:48:42.540 --> 00:48:45.490
It's almost like entering
into a dark tunnel

00:48:45.490 --> 00:48:48.760
with the hope of
sun-rays someday.

00:48:48.760 --> 00:48:50.920
So very few can make it.

00:48:50.920 --> 00:48:55.630
And there are thousands of
musicians in that journey.

00:48:55.630 --> 00:49:01.760
But my father--
we depend on God.

00:49:01.760 --> 00:49:07.240
And so whatever has happened,
with the love and blessings

00:49:07.240 --> 00:49:10.330
of the people of India,
people of the world,

00:49:10.330 --> 00:49:12.220
people who love music--

00:49:12.220 --> 00:49:15.910
and I'm grateful to
God that Amaan, Ayaan--

00:49:15.910 --> 00:49:18.382
they are so committed
and dedicated.

00:49:18.382 --> 00:49:19.840
And they are very
fortunate to have

00:49:19.840 --> 00:49:22.510
a mother like Subhalakshmi.

00:49:22.510 --> 00:49:26.260
My wife, she was a very
famous Bharatanatyam dancer.

00:49:26.260 --> 00:49:29.110
And because we both are
unemployed parents-- so we

00:49:29.110 --> 00:49:30.605
gave a lot of time to them.

00:49:30.605 --> 00:49:32.980
AMAAN ALI BANGASH: Basically,
the answer to your question

00:49:32.980 --> 00:49:35.522
is, we didn't have a
choice with the sarod.

00:49:35.522 --> 00:49:37.682
Yeah.

00:49:37.682 --> 00:49:40.215
AUDIENCE: Hello, sir,
long back in an interview,

00:49:40.215 --> 00:49:43.710
I'd seen that while training
Amaan and Ayaan, when you were

00:49:43.710 --> 00:49:45.550
traveling, probably,
you would hum a tune,

00:49:45.550 --> 00:49:47.720
and they wouldn't map
the [INAUDIBLE] to it.

00:49:47.720 --> 00:49:48.080
AMJAD ALI KHAN: Yes.

00:49:48.080 --> 00:49:48.850
AUDIENCE: Can you still do that?

00:49:48.850 --> 00:49:51.100
And if possible, can
we have a demo of that?

00:49:51.100 --> 00:49:54.070
AMJAD ALI KHAN: You're putting
us through a test again.

00:49:54.070 --> 00:49:55.745
AUDIENCE: Because I was in awe
when I saw that [INAUDIBLE]..

00:49:55.745 --> 00:49:57.619
So yeah, I don't mind
being awe-struck again.

00:49:57.619 --> 00:49:59.250
AMJAD ALI KHAN:
You see, every guru

00:49:59.250 --> 00:50:01.510
has a different way of teaching.

00:50:01.510 --> 00:50:07.660
But I feel that, more than the
language or lyrics and text,

00:50:07.660 --> 00:50:11.530
if you are a musician, you must
be connected with the sound

00:50:11.530 --> 00:50:12.370
first.

00:50:12.370 --> 00:50:14.110
Like-- Ayaan--

00:50:14.110 --> 00:50:40.150
[TARANA SINGING,
CALL &amp; RESPONSE]

00:50:40.150 --> 00:50:42.257
AMAAN ALI BANGASH: Why
did you ask this question?

00:50:42.257 --> 00:50:44.506
AMJAD ALI KHAN: We need to
do some questions with you.

00:50:47.978 --> 00:50:49.970
AUDIENCE: Thank you so much.

00:50:49.970 --> 00:50:51.950
AMJAD ALI KHAN: It's
like Musical Quiz.

00:50:51.950 --> 00:50:53.670
AYAAN ALI BANGASH: [INAUDIBLE]

00:50:53.670 --> 00:50:54.711
AMJAD ALI KHAN: So then--

00:50:54.711 --> 00:50:57.620
AYAAN ALI BANGASH: We
haven't done this in a while.

00:50:57.620 --> 00:50:59.940
AMJAD ALI KHAN: As children,
they used to do that.

00:50:59.940 --> 00:51:04.402
Now, we communicate
through instruments only.

00:51:04.402 --> 00:51:05.485
SRIDHAR RAMASWAMY: Please.

00:51:05.485 --> 00:51:08.100
AUDIENCE: Earlier, you mentioned
that your guru would ask

00:51:08.100 --> 00:51:10.290
you to surrender to the music.

00:51:10.290 --> 00:51:12.190
Those are the kind
of gurus that day.

00:51:12.190 --> 00:51:15.450
But I think, nowadays, it's hard
to find those kind of gurus.

00:51:15.450 --> 00:51:18.060
It's mostly, like, for earning.

00:51:18.060 --> 00:51:18.975
Any tips on that?

00:51:18.975 --> 00:51:22.174
Like, how to get a good
guru and get into the music?

00:51:22.174 --> 00:51:22.840
Yeah-- any tips?

00:51:22.840 --> 00:51:26.520
AMJAD ALI KHAN: There are
lots of gurus all over India,

00:51:26.520 --> 00:51:28.680
all over the world.

00:51:28.680 --> 00:51:31.800
The point is, in our
country, a learned,

00:51:31.800 --> 00:51:37.780
learned man was
considered a institution.

00:51:37.780 --> 00:51:43.510
And now, a huge cemented
building is called institution.

00:51:43.510 --> 00:51:47.350
So that is the basic difference.

00:51:47.350 --> 00:51:50.890
The institution, that
knowledgeable man--

00:51:50.890 --> 00:51:52.360
they used to be very demanding.

00:51:52.360 --> 00:51:57.070
And some gurus were very
sincere to their disciples.

00:51:57.070 --> 00:51:59.470
And some gurus are
not very sincere.

00:51:59.470 --> 00:52:01.480
We have a history
of the [INAUDIBLE]----

00:52:01.480 --> 00:52:02.850
AMAAN ALI BANGASH: That's right.

00:52:02.850 --> 00:52:03.140
AMJAD ALI KHAN: --and--

00:52:03.140 --> 00:52:04.120
AYAAN ALI BANGASH:
And [INAUDIBLE]----

00:52:04.120 --> 00:52:04.360
AMAAN ALI BANGASH: [INAUDIBLE]--

00:52:04.360 --> 00:52:05.526
AMJAD ALI KHAN: [INAUDIBLE].

00:52:05.526 --> 00:52:07.652
AMAAN ALI BANGASH: [INAUDIBLE].

00:52:07.652 --> 00:52:09.610
AMJAD ALI KHAN: So we
have that kind of history

00:52:09.610 --> 00:52:17.260
that, sometimes, guru is not
very partial or impartial.

00:52:17.260 --> 00:52:19.870
So some students
become more favorite.

00:52:19.870 --> 00:52:24.000
Some students-- they
don't want to teach them.

00:52:24.000 --> 00:52:25.930
But it's very,
very, very important

00:52:25.930 --> 00:52:30.542
to have right kind of
guidance and gurus.

00:52:30.542 --> 00:52:32.750
AMAAN ALI BANGASH: But no,
he was asking-- if I may--

00:52:32.750 --> 00:52:34.640
how to find a guru.

00:52:34.640 --> 00:52:36.800
AYAAN ALI BANGASH: You
can, of course, Google it.

00:52:36.800 --> 00:52:38.220
That's one thing.

00:52:38.220 --> 00:52:40.004
But no, seriously-- I think--

00:52:40.004 --> 00:52:41.420
AMJAD ALI KHAN:
Now, it is, people

00:52:41.420 --> 00:52:42.545
are teaching through Skype.

00:52:42.545 --> 00:52:44.003
AYAAN ALI BANGASH:
On that, I think

00:52:44.003 --> 00:52:45.710
it depends as to
where you want to go.

00:52:45.710 --> 00:52:47.400
Say, if you're learning
for the love of music,

00:52:47.400 --> 00:52:47.840
that's one thing.

00:52:47.840 --> 00:52:49.990
If you're learning because
it's a passion, it's one thing.

00:52:49.990 --> 00:52:52.490
If you're learning because you
want to make a profession out

00:52:52.490 --> 00:52:53.930
of this, then
that's another way.

00:52:53.930 --> 00:52:56.150
Then you have to learn
the way it was learned.

00:52:56.150 --> 00:52:57.900
You have to go to a teacher.

00:52:57.900 --> 00:53:00.920
You have to be a part
of that teacher's life

00:53:00.920 --> 00:53:03.000
and be around your
teacher and learn.

00:53:03.000 --> 00:53:05.950
But obviously, online
classes are happening now.

00:53:05.950 --> 00:53:07.231
It's also convenience.

00:53:07.231 --> 00:53:08.980
A lot of people have
passion, but they are

00:53:08.980 --> 00:53:10.420
unable to take that time out.

00:53:10.420 --> 00:53:14.610
So there are so many kinds
of gurus available now.

00:53:14.610 --> 00:53:16.325
But it depends which,
I think, direction

00:53:16.325 --> 00:53:17.780
you want to head towards.

00:53:17.780 --> 00:53:18.830
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:53:18.830 --> 00:53:21.710
AMJAD ALI KHAN:
Very few students

00:53:21.710 --> 00:53:26.770
are learning music
to understand music

00:53:26.770 --> 00:53:29.200
and to understand the
depth of the music.

00:53:29.200 --> 00:53:32.470
Because most of the
learners, the students,

00:53:32.470 --> 00:53:36.040
young performers-- they all
want to perform on the stage.

00:53:36.040 --> 00:53:40.030
So this impatientness to
be on the stage, that's

00:53:40.030 --> 00:53:42.600
the greatest destruction.

00:53:42.600 --> 00:53:46.166
It's a tragedy of music.

00:53:46.166 --> 00:53:47.540
SRIDHAR RAMASWAMY:
Well, we could

00:53:47.540 --> 00:53:49.600
do this for a very long time.

00:53:49.600 --> 00:53:51.080
But our time is up.

00:53:51.080 --> 00:53:53.570
It's not often that
one has the privilege

00:53:53.570 --> 00:53:57.020
to be right next to a
living legend of India.

00:53:57.020 --> 00:53:59.050
Khansa, Amaan, Ayaan--
thank you all so much.

00:53:59.050 --> 00:53:59.200
AYAAN ALI BANGASH: Thank you.

00:53:59.200 --> 00:53:59.600
AMAAN ALI BANGASH:
Thank you for having us.

00:53:59.600 --> 00:53:59.890
AMJAD ALI KHAN: Thank you.

00:53:59.890 --> 00:54:01.431
AYAAN ALI BANGASH:
Thank you so much.

00:54:01.431 --> 00:54:03.540
[APPLAUSE]

